Digitalis purpurea

   [5322.jpg]
   Authority L.
   Family Magnoliopsida:Asteridae:Scrophulariales:Scrophulariaceae
   Synonyms
   Common names common foxglove, purple foxglove, foxglove, foxes glofa
   (Anglo-Saxon), witches' glove, dead man's bells, bloody fingers, bloody
   man's fingers, flapdock, fairy glove, fairy finger, finger flower, lady
   glove, Roter Fingerhut, Fingerkraut, Waldglocke, Waldglöckchen,
   Waldschelle, Unserliebenfrauenhandschuh, Digitale pourpré, Digitale
   rossa, dedaleira, digitalis, cacapeiro, dedalario, erva dedal,
   estoura-fole, luvas de Santa Maria, luvas de pastora, Almindelig
   fingerbøl, Fingerbøl, Rød fingerbøl, Fingerborgsblomma, Revebjølle,
   Revebjelle, Fingurbjargablóm, Fingurbjargarblóm, Rohtosormustinkukka,
   Sormustinkukka, Naparstnica purpurowa, Naparstnik, Echte
   Vingerhoedskruid, Vingerhoedskruid soort, Dedalera, Potschen
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 5322

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION An erect herb. The stem may in the second year reach
   100-200 cm in height. The inflorescence is a one side terminal raceme
   with bell-shaped, dark red, whitish or pink flowers. USES The dried
   leaves are used medically for their effects on the central nervous
   system, and the heart and blood vessels. It is often planted as an
   ornamnetal. GROWING PERIOD Perennial or biennial. Leaves are collected
   from two year old plants. The plant may live for 3-4 years. COMMON
   NAMES Common foxglove, Digitalis, Foxglove. FURTHER INF Common foxglove
   is native of western Europe. It is found growing wild in open woods,
   heaths, and hedgebanks. The expected yield is 1.5-2.5 t/ha of dry
   leaves.

   Sources
   SOURCES (D. purpurea L.)
